            <biogHist>
                <p>Somhairle MacCalmain also appears in official records as Somerled MacCalamain and
                    Samuel Murchison. He was born around 1775 to Donald Murchison, farmer, and
                    Catherine Murchison n√©e Bethune in Duirnish parish, Isle of Skye. He is recorded
                    in the 1841 census as Samuel Murchison, farmer, aged 65, living at Lionacleit,
                    Benbecula. His wife was Catherine (60) and his children John (20), Mary (20),
                    Flory (15), all of whom were born in the county of Inverness-shire. Also living
                    at the address are Samuel MacRae aged 2 and John MacIntyre (15) and a male
                    servant, both also born in Inverness-shire. In the 1851 census, the family is
                    still living at Lionacleit. Samuel is aged 77 and recorded as a crofter born in
                    Skye. His wife Catherine (74); his son John (32), who is described as being
                    employed at home; and daughter Flora (25) are all recorded as being born in
                    South Uist parish, Flora and John being unmarried. Donald MacRae aged 8 and a
                    scholar is described as a visitor also born in South Uist parish. </p>
                <p>Somhairle was predeceased by his wife by a few months. He died of natural decay
                    in August 1855 and he was buried at Cladh Mhuire, Benbecula.</p>
                <p>Somhairle MacCalmain is mentioned in manuscripts by Dugald MacAulay, Hacleit,
                    Benbecula from whom Alexander Carmichael collected verses which MacAulay styled
                    'Altach Somhairle Mac Calmain'. </p>
